If you want to omit the extra `src` and `test` folders under `dist`, you&#39;ll want to tell `tsc`, that it should only compile the files under `src` with the given `tsconfig.json`. 

As a default, the compiler includes all files in the project workspace, so it needs the extra folder structure to distinguish `src` from `test`. That is also the reason, why there isn&#39;t any `src` folder in `dist` created, when `speed-test.ts` is deleted - all files are under `src` now, so the compiler chooses this directory as the root.  You can restrict compilation to `src` only via [`include/exclude/files`][1] compiler option like this:
```
{
    &quot;compilerOptions&quot;: {
      ...
    },
    &quot;include&quot;: [
        &quot;src/**/*&quot;
    ]
}
```

With [`rootDir`][2] you can additionally enforce that the parent directory for your output in `dist` will always be `src`, even if you should accidently `import` something from outside `src` in one of your modules (if not specified, `rootDir` is automatically calculated as the parent directory of all inputs). In this case `tsc` would abort compilation, as `rootDir` is not the root of all input files anymore.
```
{
  &quot;compilerOptions&quot;: {
    &quot;rootDir&quot;: &quot;src&quot;,
    ...
  }
}
```

For your test files, you can do a separate compilation step with a different  configuration like `tsconfig.test.json` (or via `tsc` CLI). E.g. with jest, [here][3] is an example with a custom configuration file. Or you could just use `tsc` CLI to compile `speed-test.ts` and then use the test tool of choice (not sure what that is for you).

Hope, that helps!

  [1]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/tsconfig-json.html#examples
  [2]: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/compiler-options.html
  [3]: https://kulshekhar.github.io/ts-jest/user/config/tsConfig

